We need our Black community to understand and challenge our own participation in the oppression of multiply-marginalised Black people. 

BLMUK is a very diverse team and we would like to make it clear that we are here for the liberation of ALL Black people.

We ask that people are respectful in all campaigns, events, protests and online and offline interactions that use #BlackLivesMatter. We ask that everyone fighting for Black lives takes note of this statement and uses it in their own organising.

It’s important for us to understand the diversity of Blackness and to protect, support and accept all of our Black family. We will not tolerate any oppressive behaviour, abuse or hate within our spaces or on our platforms.

This includes but is not limited to, homophobia, lesbophobia, biphobia, queerphobia, transphobia, sexism, misogyny, misogynoir, enbyphobia, ableism, racism, anti-Blackness, islamophobia, whorephobia, ageism, fatphobia, eugenics, discrimination, stereotypes ...

stigmatisation of HIV, stigmatisation of addiction etc. We won’t tolerate verbal or physical abuse, bullying or attacks.

We need to protect, uplift & platform our marginalised Black fam. 

Marginalised Black fam consistently show up for us all & we need to show up for them too!
If you are organising events or running platforms, please make sure you include safer spaces policies/ safety contacts/ statements on inclusivity so that you can ensure that your events are safe
and that people know to challenge, remove and hold accountable any disruptive, violent and oppressive behaviour. If you are struggling with finding ways to implement inclusivity policies, reach out.

#BlackLivesMatter was created by Black women in response to institutional racism. Police brutality has killed countless Black women as well as Black men. Breonna Taylor. Sandra Bland. Tanisha Anderson. Michelle Cusseaux. Bettie Jones. Dominique Clayton. Tiara Thomas. India Kager.

#BlackLivesMatter  was founded by three Black women: Alicia Garza, Patrisse Cullors, and Opal Tometi. Though they are often erased - which happens a lot to Black women - they are the creators of what has grown into an international movement guided by Black feminist principles.

#BlackLivesMatter was created by Black women in response to institutional racism. Police brutality has killed countless Black women as well as Black men. Breonna Taylor. Sandra Bland. Tanisha Anderson. Michelle Cusseaux. Bettie Jones. Dominique Clayton. Tiara Thomas. India Kager.

African-American women are regularly killed by police brutality. Yet their names often slip out of public consciousness, their murders go unprotested. The African-American Policy Forum, founded by Kimberlé Crenshaw, began #SayHerName to challenge both this violence and erasure.

In addition to being killed and beaten by police, Black women are at risk of sexual violence. Daniel Holtzclaw isn’t the only officer to have abused his power in this way. But many white feminists who are vocal opponents of male violence stay quiet if the victims are Black women.

Police brutality and male violence against women are not separate issues. Women in relationships with police officers are significantly more likely to experience intimate partner violence than women in relationships with civilian men. This is a well documented phenomenon.

Treating manhood as the default setting of Blackness and whiteness and as the default setting of womanhood - aside from showing very limited imagination and empathy - reinforces the hierarchies that lead to violence against Black women. That’s not liberation politics.

It’s so revealing that instead of challenging any of the white men who are overrepresented in every last sphere of public discourse, these white feminists grudged focus on #BlackLivesMatter in the aftermath of George Floyd’s murder. They chose whiteness as a political priority.

The same white feminists who complain about #BlackLivesMatter gaining momentum would never have thought to centre the experiences of Black women when #MeToo entered the mainstream. And plenty of them erased Tarana Burke, the Black woman who spent years building that movement.

And I didn’t include handles or quote tweet because, although furious with the casual anti-Blackness on display, I don’t want to cause a pile on. It would be nice to see more white women work out how to use their platforms responsibly when dealing with Black women. Fin.
